			<title>Why video games can never be art</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?74875-Why-video-games-can-never-be-art&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 11 Mar 2013 23:31:15 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I have to first apologize for being disingenuous. I don't believe they can't be art as much as I believe there are things that keep most of them from being art. I also need to apologize because this topic bores me to tears and I made a thread on it anyway. :p 
 
The principal problem is the fact...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I have to first apologize for being disingenuous. I don't believe they can't be art as much as I believe there are things that keep most of them from being art. I also need to apologize because this topic bores me to tears and I made a thread on it anyway. :p<br />
<br />
The principal problem is the fact that they are first and foremost a product. Games are made to be enjoyed, because most people do not want to spend money on something that makes them feel anything but good. It's the same human failing that ensures the hero will always be incredibly beautiful, and why there is often pushback when the main character is someone the audience dislikes.<br />
<br />
So for example, in the anime Neon Genesis Evangelion, the main character is a whiny little good-for-nothing shit. He also represents the viewer. Audiences like a main character they can relate to while also feeling good about themselves through association. While they can relate to someone with negative qualities, it's usually a very hard sell to convince them to do so, because most people consume entertainment to feel good. But art does more than make you feel good, it makes you feel bad too, it makes you feel any range of emotions the artist wants you to feel. <br />
<br />
So getting back to my main point, most video games are made to be products. They are often changed radically during prototyping in order to better appeal to their chosen audience. A game that fails to do this is often ridiculed a great deal at best. Can Mass Effect 3 really be art if customers can demand the ending be changed because they didn't like it? <br />
<br />
Another example occurred to me while playing Tomb Raider. Sometime last year there was a lot of controversy over a scene in which Lara is groped by a murderer, the representative being interviewed implied that the scene showed how desperate Lara's growth as a character had to be. That at the threat of rape she was forced to kill for the first time.<br />
<br />
People went ballistic. They were outraged at the very idea of such a thing being in a video game. Some were offended at the portrayal of women. Others thought such a thing should never be addressed in a video game in the first place. I always thought this was strange, as although I despise the subject matter myself, I don't see how anyone can take the medium seriously if you need to use baby gloves while handling serious issues. Can something be art if it is unable to address something that might make the player feel bad? <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Of course there are always exceptions, even ignoring indie games which for the most part aren't constrained with the same limitations of needing to be profitable to exist.<br />
<br />
I was explaining the plot to Metal Gear Solid 2 to someone the other day, when it occurred to me that maybe a video game can be art just by making the player uncomfortable and by refusing to give them what they expect. Players wanted to play as Solid Snake but could not, and this denial in itself was a metaphor for the plot as revealed later in the game. That by controlling the information a person has access to, you control what they do. It wasn't just the player character that the game implied had been controlled, but the players themselves. <br />
<br />
Spec Ops: The Line is another example of a game that can be considered art through the act of deception. The game is basically a modern military first person shooter that cleverly criticizes the reason why most people play modern military first person shooters.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>Spec Ops spoilers</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
<br />
By the end of Spec Ops: The Line, you realize that much of the horrible things that occur only happened because your character got caught up in a wish fulfillment fantasy in which they were a hero. <br />
 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
<br />
I had a great example a week ago when I first started putting these thoughts together, but I've lost it now. I was impressed because the gameplay itself was art. Not the story or the world, the way you actually play the game. Burn me for forgetting it.<br />
<br />
Anyway in conclusion, art is not constrained by the whims of the people who consume it, and most video games are.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
