			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I think this may be a long shot, but my Google-fu is failing me.<br />
<br />
A year or two ago I was playing an online RPG of sorts.  It was free, but had daily limits on the amount of turns you could take.  If you've played Legend of the Green Dragon, you have the right idea.  <br />
<br />
This game had various cities you could travel to, and had dungeons and such you could go through.  Not exactly 'explore', as it was just a matter of one room detailed in text leading to another room detailed in text, but it was still fun.  There were stats for your characters, <font color="#FF0000">Strength</font>, <font color="#008000">Dexterity</font>, <font color="#0000FF">Intelligence</font>, etc.  As your stats went up, your character level did too.  <br />
<br />
The most defining part of the game was the cards - you built a deck out of them and those determined your attacks and what not.  What cards you could use was determined by your stats -for instance, swords might require a mix of Strength and Dexterity, while axes might be pure strength but more of it.  You got cards from doing dungeons and quests.  You could also attack other players, pitting your deck against theirs.  <br />
<br />
I'm fairly certain the game's name started with an 'E', but don't quote me on that.<br />
<br />
Anyways, I don't suppose there's a shot anyone knows what I'm talking about and can point me in the right direction?</div>

]]></content:encoded>
