		<item>
			<title><![CDATA[March '13 Release Thread]]></title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?74829-March-13-Release-Thread&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 27 Feb 2013 23:45:54 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>March is the month where publishers lose their minds. So desperate to get as far away from Call of Duty as possible, while also getting good numbers at the end of the fiscal year, they all release their games all at once. The number of releases is staggering, arguably as much as the rest of the...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>March is the month where publishers lose their minds. So desperate to get as far away from Call of Duty as possible, while also getting good numbers at the end of the fiscal year, they all release their games all at once. The number of releases is staggering, arguably as much as the rest of the year combined.<br />
<br />
The two biggest games this month, in my mind, are Bioshock Infinite and the Tomb Raider reboot. Bioshock being a long time in coming, and arguably one of the sure things this year. Tomb Raider is going to be more divisive. It marks a shift towards more action and less puzzles (the puzzles being completely optional). Some people are going to love it, and some are going to hate it. It seems to be poised to be a nominee for &quot;game of the year&quot; all the same.<br />
<br />
But this is a great month for exclusives as well: God of War and Gears of War both get a new game for the PS3 and 360 respectively. Amusingly enough, both are also prequels, with Gears of War focusing on the series side characters during the initial invasion, and God of War taking place 10 years before the first game. Supposedly they are going to attempt to paint Kratos as a more human character this time. Ascension will also be notable for being the first God of War with multiplayer. It almost seems to be the point of the game, rather than just a gimmick tacked on.<br />
<br />
PCs have a big month as well. Starcraft 2: Heart of the Swarm, the new Sim City, and the Resident Evil 6 port are all due this month. And while it is technically multiplatform, Metro: Last Light will definitely be best on PC (if it actually comes out this month that is).<br />
<br />
On the Nintendo front, the Wii in the US is getting Pandora's Tower, one of the titles in the fan PR campaign &quot;operation rainfall&quot; that Europe got a year ago. It will be the last title that fans petitioned to be brought over actually, so that makes operation rainfall a complete success. That's notable in and of itself, is it not? <br />
<br />
The Wii U gets a GTA for kids in the form of Lego City Undercover. I'm as sick of Lego games as anyone else, but I'm optimistic for this one, I think it looks good.<br />
<br />
The 3DS also has several titles coming out this month. Most notable Luigi's Mansion, followed by a Pokemon spinoff and a Castlevania game. The latter could be either amazing or mediocre, going to wait and see on that one.<br />
<br />
And finally, as always download only titles are hard to track and I will post as I hear about them, but Darkstalkers is due an HD remake/port for XBLA and PSN this month, supposedly.<br />
<br />
Games not mentioned: Army of Two, Lost Planet 3, Naruto Fighter 3, MLB The Show, Atelier Ayesha, Monster Hunter 3 Wii U port, Dead or Alive 5 vita port<br />
<br />
P.S. Wii U getting several ports, including Aliens Colonial Marines. :evil:<br />
<br />
